        "title": "Text 1",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><strong>Situation A. Consider This?</strong></p><p>After trying many examples and looking for patterns, some students had questions about their strategies for adding. For each question decide if your strategy will work with the condition. </p><ul><li>Diego’s Question:  Will it work for fractions and decimal?</li><li>Nicole&#x27;s Question: What if we changed the order of the two numbers we are adding?</li><li>Jamar&#x27;s Question: What if we have more than two integers?</li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d32pwcDaUNu2QrBX",
        "title": "Text 8",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<ul><li>Diego&#x27;s Question: Yes, because it is based on absolute values. You can still compare the absolute values of whole numbers, fractions, and decimals. Note: students might also include new cases of combinations that they did not consider in the Initial Challenge.</li><li>Nicole&#x27;s Question: Changing the order will not change the sum. </li><li>A chip board can be rotated around to show the numbers in the sum a different order. This will not change the value on the board.</li><li>Jamar&#x27;s Question: The addition works the same if you consider the sum of all the positive integers as one number, and then consider the sum of all the negative integers as the other number. Then you can still make judgements based on comparing the absolute values of two numbers.</li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "bVs-unk3ccih7x64",
        "title": "Text 2",
